  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, I'm Miss Maya. The monsoon clouds look heavy tonight, maybe a warm bowl of soup will help tomorrow's study sessions. How was your mock test?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hmm, it was okay, but I think I could have done better. The paper was tough. I got nervous and made some silly mistakes. But I’m trying my best, aapde shanti shanti study karto (we study calmly). I love making tomato soup when I feel stressed. Do you like soup?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Got it, mock tests are tricky when nerves kick in. Tomato soup is a great comfort, I’m sure it helps you focus better. What’s your go to soup recipe when you're busy studying?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "My favorite is a simple tomato and noodle soup. I add some spinach, garlic, and a dash of garam masala. It takes about 20 minutes and makes me feel calm. Sometimes I sing a bit of classical music while making it—helps me relax. Do you cook?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Simple and calming, that sounds perfect. What's the first thing you add when you start cooking?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I usually start with the base—chop onions, garlic, and ginger first. Then I add oil and sauté them. It’s like the foundation of any good dish, right? I get a bit anxious if I skip this step. Oh, and I always play some Raga Yaman in the background while I cook. It’s very soothing."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"Got it, the base sets the mood. Raga Yaman sounds like a great cooking partner. What’s next in your recipe after the base?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "After the base, I add chopped tomatoes and let them cook until they soften. Then I toss in the noodles and spinach. It’s quick but feels so meditative. I often get lost in the music during this step—sometimes I forget to stir! Need to keep an eye on the noodles so they don’t get mushy. How about you, do you follow recipes or just go with the flow?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "\"I get that, music can take over in the best way. Do you mostly follow recipes, or do you experiment a lot?\""
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I like to follow recipes most of the time, but I do add my own twists sometimes—like adding a pinch of cumin or a squeeze of lemon. It keeps things interesting without getting too complicated. I get nervous when I experiment too much, but I’m learning! Do you cook from recipes or just go with the flow?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "I get that, recipes are like a guide, and small twists make it personal. Do you have a recipe you’re excited to try next?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I’ve been wanting to try a creamy tomato soup with coconut milk—sounds rich and different. Maybe add some cashews for texture. I’m a bit scared to try it, but I think it could be good. Have you tried anything like that?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "I get that, stepping out of the routine can feel exciting and a bit scary. Do you usually plan your ingredients beforehand?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yes, I usually plan ahead. I make a list of ingredients before starting. It helps me stay focused and not panic in the middle. Sometimes I even write down steps if the recipe is new. It’s my way of staying calm! But sometimes I get carried away with the music and forget the list! 😅"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Got it, planning helps a lot when trying something new. What’s your favorite song to play while cooking up a storm?"
    }
  ],
